<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-550-101  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 550 101.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Oct 29 1990 v7 n42 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Visix updates Looking Glass GUI; inks sales deal with DEC. (DEC tosell Visix Software's Looking Glass 2.0 graphical user interfacefor Ultrix-based systems) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Visix Software introduces Looking Glass 2.0, a graphical userinterface (GUI) ranging in price from $595 to $795.andP;  The newsoftware runs on DEC's Ultrix-based systems and will be sold byDEC for three years under a recently signed marketing agreement.andO;The icon- and mouse-driven interface is touted as easy to use andfully compliant with the Open Software Foundation's Motif GUIstandard.andP;  The software is expected to increase the marketabilityof DEC's Ultrix workstations and X terminals.andP;  Files can be calledup more quickly in the updated version, and the program'sappearance is more three-dimensional.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (Marketing)Visix Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Product:   Looking Glass 2.0 (Graphical user interface) (Productintroduction)Ultrix (Operating system) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceMarketing AgreementsContracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Visix updates Looking Glass GUI; inks sales deal with DECandM;NEW YORK -- Visix Software this week will release version 2.0 of its LookingGlass graphical user environment at Unix Expo, and at the same time announcethat DEC has signed a three-year deal to sell Looking Glass for Ultrixbasedsystems.andM;Under the agreement, Looking Glass will be sold by the DEC sales force, amove that should make Ultrix workstations and X terminals more  attractive tothe average end user.andM;Looking Glass 2.0, which is also available for Sun, IBM and other Unixplatforms, is an icon- and mouse-driven graphical user interface for Unixthat is as easy to use as a Macintosh interface, according to Visixofficials.andM;The program fully complies with the Open Software Foundation's Motifgraphical user interface standard, the officials said.andM;Looking Glass 2.0 will make Unix workstations more attractive to somecustomers who might  traditionally have purchased Macintoshes or IBM PCsrunning Windows 3.0 or Presentation Manager from Microsoft, according tocompany officials.andM;Features in Version 2.0 of Looking Glass include the ability to call up afile by typing enough letters in its name to distinguish the file fromothers.andP;  The updated version also includes a more distinctivethree-dimensional appearance.andM;Seeing through Tree ViewsandM;The program now offers a graphical tree view of the file system that allowsusers to browse by opening icons that show contents of directories.andM;A user can open, merge, save and close trees, and revert to the last-savedTree View configuration.andP;  Tree Views can be shown by name and icon.andM;Looking Glass 2.0 also includes a color menu so that users can assign colorsto files and directories.andP;  The Sort menu also now allows users to sort bycolor.andM;Double clicking on a Wide View column heading will cause the directory windowto be sorted by that category.andM;In addition, the Select By Pattern dialogue now includes a history list ofrecently used search patterns.andM;Users are also able to import and export icon-sized bit map images.andP;  Userscan also now merge two or more icon galleries.andM;Fifty icons have been added to the program.andM;Future versions of Looking Glass are likely to include support for multimediaapplications, according to company officials.andM;Looking Glass version 2.0 is available now.andP;  Prices range from $595 to $795.andM;Upgrades are also now available.andM;For more information, Visix Software Inc. can be contacted at 11440 CommercePark Drive, Reston, VA 22091, (709) 758-2700.andO;</TEXT></DOC>